ns between the US South and the plantation zones of Mexico, places that suffered parallel problems of environmental decline, rural poverty, and gross inequities in land tenure. Bringing this tumultuous era vividly to life, he describes how Roosevelt's New Deal drew on Mexican revolutionary agrarianism to shape its program for the rural South. Olsson also looks at how the US South served as the domestic laboratory for the Rockefeller Foundation's "green revolution" in Mexico-which would become the most important Third World development campaign of the twentieth century-and how the Mexican government attempted to replicate the hydraulic development of the Tennessee Valley Authority after World War II.Rather than a comparative history, Agrarian Crossings is an innovative history of comparisons and the ways they affected policy, moved people, and reshaped the landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAgriculture and statezMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aAgriculture and statezSouthern StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLand reformzMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aLand reformzSouthern StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLand use, RuralzMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aLand use, RuralzSouthern StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aAmerican.  aCold War.  aFarm Security Administration.  aFrank Tannenbaum.  aGeneral Education Board.  aJosephus Daniels.  aLatin American.  aMexican Agricultural Program.  aMexican Revolution.  aMexican agrarian reform.  aMexican countryside.  aMexico.  aMiguel Alemán.  aNew Deal politics.  aNew Deal.  aRockefeller Foundation.  aSouthern Tenant Farmers' Union.  aTennessee Valley Authority.  aUS Populist movement.  aUS South.  aUnited States.  aagrarian justice.  aagrarian policy.  aagrarian radicalism.  a